<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Further submission from Sheffield City Council</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="color:#808080; font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">LGO82</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Further submission from Sheffield City Council</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Moor Market, Sheffield </span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Note on EU Procurement Issues</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Background</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sheffield City Council (SCC) had</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> long term aspiration to move</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> its</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> indoor market from Castle Market to north east of city centre to the bottom of the Moor in the south east of the centre on a site known as “Block 6”. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Block 6 formed part of a long lease</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the whole of the Moor</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> granted by SCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> (as freeholder)</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> in 1996 and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owned by German investor RREEF (part of Deut</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">s</span><a name="_GoBack"></a><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">che Bank)</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">During the mid</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2000’s, SCC treated with RREEF with a view to RREEF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> developing a new market building for SCC on block 6 to be purchased by SCC on co</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">mpletion of the building. RREEF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> appointed its own desi</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">gn team and worked up various schemes for the new market. H</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">owever, partly because of RREEF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s main interests being as an investor rather than a </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">developer as well as the property market crash of 2008</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> and, ultimately, its intention to dispose of its interest,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> the scheme did not progress.</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> 2010</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> R</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">REEF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> sold its long leasehold interest to Scottish widows Investment Partnership Property Trust (SWIPPT) which had a proactive plan for investment in and development of The Moor and desire actively to engage with SCC i</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">n relation to the development of Block 6 and other sites on The Moor.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SWIPPT took over</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> most of RREEF</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">’s professional team and worked up plans for bock 6 to develop a new 75,000 sq ft indoor market for SCC along with 8 new unit shops and a shared service yar</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">d.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">EU Procurement Issue</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">By the time that SCC was in a position to take a proposal for SWIPPT to develop the new market on block 6 for SCC to Cabinet for approval</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, the c</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ase</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Auroux</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> v. Commune de Roa</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">nne (2007</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">) and a number of other related EU procurement </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">cases had begun to highlight the potential risk of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> non compliance with EU Public Procurement Rules in procuring works that might be const</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">r</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ued as “Public Works”. There was a perceived risk of</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> challenge to the </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">council to</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> procuring a building for its own use,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> to a specification required by SCC via a development agreement with a developer not chosen</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> through an EU compliant</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> competitive marketing</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> exercise</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">. This risk was highlighted by SCC Legal Services with the benefit of advice from external lawyers.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Potential </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">solutions explored</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SCC shared its concerns with SWIPPT and sought ways to proceed with the market scheme at the preferred location</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The possibility of the potential to offer the market development to the property development market in Sheffield , ie to seek</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> proposals on other sites controlled by other landowners/developers in Sheffield, was considered but rejected as Block 6 </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">was the council’s preferred location and no other sites in the City were believed to be as good.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">SCC then proposed to SWIPPT that, inst</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">ead of SWIPPT developing the whole of Block 6 and selling the market building to SCC</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> that the deal be “flipped” with SCC developing the whole site and selling the shop element to SWIPPT. This was rejected by SWIPPT as it was not prepared to cede control o</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">f its retail development to SCC</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Agreed procurement solution</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Following further discussions between SCC and SWIPPT, a compromise solution was agreed under which SCC took a surrender of the long lease to SWIPPT of the site of the proposed market so that SCC </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">could develop its new market on its own site in possession so as not to be in the position of procuring a building, specified by SCC, from which to provide a service via a property transaction entered into without competition</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> SCC also became the developer</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of the service yard – jointly funded by SWIPPT- with SWIPPT itself developing the shops. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The building contractor for all elements of the Block 6 scheme (ie market, shops and service yard) was jointly procured </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">by SCC and SWIPPT via a fully </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">EU compliant </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">tendering process with the outcome being “one contractor,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> two clients,</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> three contracts” on the same development plot. </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> </span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 21pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-weight:bold">Issues highlighted</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">The “one contractor, two clients, three contracts” solution has been made to work helped by a high level of trust and</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> goodwill built up between SCC, SWIPPT and the contractor. However, the legal documentation and financial and constructional monitoring of this procurement route was considerably more complicated and time consuming than it would have been if there had not </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">been a perceived risk of challenge under EU procurement driving this method of procurement.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 31.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">In </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">addition, in dealing with Sheffield’s New Retail Quarter, there is a move generally, across the UK, to use the EU procurement process to secure a developer, whic</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">h in the most part is a way of disposing of land (land transactions being exempt from EU procurement rules). In most cases, as is the intent with Sheffield, the Public Sector is not actually procuring anything, it is selling a piece of land, however we are</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> all using the EU procurement rules to deliver development and the process is both time consuming and costly. A review of this area – property development, would be useful to assist with controlling costs and helping the delivery process.</span></li></ul><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Nigel Cunis</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Head</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt"> of Asset Strategy and Commercial Property</span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt">Sheffield City Council</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Arial; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">28 November 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:center"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">1</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>